68    /**
69    * <p>
70    * This is an attempt at covering most particular cases of combining two
71    * values. Here {@code x} is the value returned by
72    * {@link #getPreferredEntryValue()}, while {@code y} and {@code z} are two
73    * "normal" values.
74    * </p>
75    * <ol>
76    * <li>
77    * Addition: the following cases should be covered
78    * <ul>
79    * <li>{@code (2 * x) + (-x)}</li>
80    * <li>{@code (-x) + 2 * x}</li>
81    * <li>{@code x + y}</li>
82    * <li>{@code y + x}</li>
83    * <li>{@code y + z}</li>
84    * <li>{@code y + (x - y)}</li>
85    * <li>{@code (y - x) + x}</li>
86    * </ul>
87    * The values to be considered are:
88    * {@code x, y, z, 2 * x, -x, x - y, y - x}.
89    * </li>
90    * <li>
91    * Subtraction: the following cases should be covered
92    * <ul>
93    * <li>{@code (2 * x) - x}</li>
94    * <li>{@code x - y}</li>
95    * <li>{@code y - x}</li>
96    * <li>{@code y - z}</li>
97    * <li>{@code y - (y - x)}</li>
98    * <li>{@code (y + x) - y}</li>
99    * </ul>
100    * The values to be considered are: {@code x, y, z, x + y, y - x}.
101    * </li>
102    * <li>
103    * Multiplication
104    * <ul>
105    * <li>{@code (x * x) * (1 / x)}</li>
106    * <li>{@code (1 / x) * (x * x)}</li>
107    * <li>{@code x * y}</li>
108    * <li>{@code y * x}</li>
109    * <li>{@code y * z}</li>
110    * </ul>
111    * The values to be considered are: {@code x, y, z, 1 / x, x * x}.
112    * </li>
113    * <li>
114    * Division
115    * <ul>
116    * <li>{@code (x * x) / x}</li>
117    * <li>{@code x / y}</li>
118    * <li>{@code y / x}</li>
119    * <li>{@code y / z}</li>
120    * </ul>
121    * The values to be considered are: {@code x, y, z, x * x}.
122    * </li>
123    * </ol>
124    * Also to be considered {@code NaN}, {@code POSITIVE_INFINITY},
125    * {@code NEGATIVE_INFINITY}, {@code +0.0}, {@code -0.0}.
126    */
127    private final double[] values;
